<br />
We have them because once these balancing passes are finished, the &quot;best&quot; dps should come from having one of EACH caster present in the raid force, rather than stacking multiples.<br />
<br />
<br />
Sorcerers should deal the best over time and direct damage, but with out the other 3 casters, they will miss crucial buffs, hate mitigation, and debuff that would be avalible.<br />
<br />
Necromancer should be close behind sorcerers when comparing over time damage, and they will offer good buffs and debuffs for everyone to benefit from.<br />
<br />
Druids should be close behind sorcerers when comparing max DPS capability, and should also bring buffs/debuffs that improve the over all dps of the raid.<br />
<br />
Psionicists should be a fair distance behinds sorcerers in max dps as well as over time dps, to the extent of how a bard is behind a ranger, but they should have the most potient spell-damage-boosting effects in the game, meaning that any group that is set up for spell dps will do better with a psionicist than with replacing them with a multiple of an existing class.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Aka:<br />
<br />
Sorc / Sorc / Sorc / Sroc should be less dps than Sorc / Psion / Druid / Necro.<br />
<br />
<br />
More so, any multiples of a class should be less effective than diversity when it comes to total damage brought to the raid:<br />
<br />
Sorc x4 &lt; sorc x3 + druid / necro / psion <br />
<br />
Or any multiples.<br />
<br />
four of the same class should be weaker, when gear and skill are equal, should always be weaker than even the substitution of just one different class*<br />
<br />
This excludes &quot;specific&quot; fights in which one class might have a huge advantage, like double damage on a particular Element they are strong in, like a double-arcane damage mob, x4 sorcerers would be strong, though the addition of a psionicist would still produce more total dps than just adding an extra sorcerer, and likely the same would be true for a druid as well)
                  
		</div>
