		<div id="post_message_1287269">
                  
                  *shrug*<br />
<br />
Doesnt matter what we feel should be the DPS ladder, its going to have casters at the top, with the exception of the psionicist being under the rogue.<br />
<br />
<br />
There are plenty of reasons as to &quot;why&quot; this is im sure, and we could speculate about it all day, but thats probably such a fundamental design, with all the changes currently being designed, that they cannt just reverse that decision.<br />
<br />
<br />
Rogues actually offer quite a bit to a raid imo, at least i certainly notice their contributions.<br />
<br />
The raid wide +4% crit is nice, as are their debuffs to an extent, and Imperil is amazing.<br />
<br />
I would say that a rogue most certainly &quot;contributes&quot; more dps to the raid than a druid or sorcerer does. Contributes defined as your buffs and debuffs that facilitate damage, of which a sorcerer has none, and the druid has a minor str/dex/haste componant on wolf form as well as their procs, and a resistance debuff on their dot, and thats it.<br />
<br />
The actual &quot;DPS&quot; your character does is important, but its not the only factor.<br />
<br />
If your presence and debuffs improve each person's individual dps by even as little as +100 dps, multiply that by 17 people and toss that on to your personal dps, and look how that stacks up.<br />
<br />
I would definatly venture a guess that the druid's resistance debuff, and minor stat buffs, and proc add less dps than a rogues +4% crit and imperil.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
