<tr valign="top">
	<td class="alt2" width="175">
	
	
			<div id="postmenu_1287321">
				
				
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?u=13001">jhorry</a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_1287321", true); </script>
				
			</div>
			
			<div class="smallfont">Forum Channeler</div>
			
			
			
		




			<div class="smallfont">

<!-- Profiles -->
 
<!-- / Profiles -->



				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>   </div>
			</div>				
	
	
	
	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1287321">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1287321">
                  
                  Some people simply wont grasp certain concepts, such as personal dps + provided dps = net dps.<br />
<br />
<br />
Bards, in a since, as well as a clerics to a degree, are overpowered in the shear amount of damage they can bring to a raid by their inclusion.<br />
<br />
+50% damage is a serious amount, and the fact that with just bard and cleric buffs alone more than doubles my dps as a disciple should be fact alone that they are plain and simply contributing a tad too much.<br />
<br />
Heck, as a disciple i would be THRILLED if i could just use my bonds to improve ONE person's dps by 40%, much less improving an entire group's dps.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Balance is such a tricky issue though.<br />
<br />
Obviously you dont want to &quot;nerf&quot; (god i hate that word) bards to a point where they are undesirable for their primary purposes, which is to enhance melee dps classes, but in the same respect you dont want them to be so powerful that they are almost required to deal with encounters that are balanced TO the amount of dps they provide.<br />
<br />
If a raid with 3 bards can provide on average enough damage to slay a foe in a certain time limit, and this becomes the &quot;norm&quot; for developers, then the majority of 'difficult&quot; content will be designed to be killed in this fast time limit.<br />
<br />
If a raid is balanced to have one or no bards expected, then the addition of one or multiple bards might make killing the foe in the alloted time highly trivial.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Anyway im getting off topic.<br />
<br />
<br />
They topic we should be focused on is this:<br />
<br />
<br />
ALL damage-based classes are comprised of two generalized methods-<br />
<br />
1.) Damage Generater.<br />
<br />
This is the actual damage production, your personal dps. <br />
<br />
<br />
and <br />
<br />
2.) Damage Enabler.<br />
<br />
This is the damage augmentation via buffs and debuffs that strongly influences the generated damage.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
When classes are truely balanced, with the case of 4 classes, you should find the following to be true:<br />
<br />
You have one class priamrily devoted to Damage Generation with highly limited damage enabling.<br />
<br />
2 classes that are some where in the middle, generally being heavy on Damage Generation, with one focusing on &quot;enhancing&quot; and the other on &quot;enfeebling.&quot;<br />
<br />
Finally you have one class that is strongly focused on Damage Enabling and mediocre at Damage Generating.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
By combining all four methods, you achieve the HIGHEST possible net gain in terms of dps.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
That means that if the Rogue is ment to be the &quot;top personal dps,&quot; then they should be limited in the extent of how they can improve other classes.<br />
<br />
Rangers should be close to a rogues &quot;fast&quot; dps, and should be able to spike higher than monks, and aid in damage Enabling by buffing their allies, which they do very well actually.<br />
<br />
Monks should be close to a rogue's sustain dps, and should be able to keep a high, constant dps that superceeds the ranger. They should focus on Damage Enabling by weakening their foes, allowing every to strike them harder (initially the weakness system was to be their method)<br />
<br />
Bards should be noticably below the other 3 fighters in spike and sustained dps, which i believe everyone can agree they are, and they should both enhance allies and weaken foes well enough to strongly influence the damage of their allies.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I personally think bards make a bit too much of a difference, to the point that &quot;not&quot; having a bard is just plain stupidity. They should make a noticable difference, but their absence should not be the downfall of a raid; we are not to have any &quot;required&quot; class in any point in the game.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
The exact same applies to casters, just replace rogue with sorcerer, Ranger with druid, monk with necromancer, and psionicist (post revamp hopefully, NOT the current form) with Bard.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
As for &quot;why&quot; a caster would have a higher damage potiential than a melee class, some reasons that i could rationalize, but which would need to be made more of an issue in a raiding enviornment:<br />
<br />
1.) Survivability. <br />
<br />
I APPROVE of having aoes that effect the whole raid. Silencing, spell reflecting, high resistance, LONG ranger aoes that dont effect people near the foe, and other such anti-ranged tactics should be on more foes. For every foe that is &quot;deadly&quot; to melee people, their needs to be an antithesis for ranged fighters. IMO range should not equal safety, as that creates imbalances. <br />
<br />
Why should a ranged player need defense or health if their distance is their ultimant defense, would that not allow them to focus on more offensive gear that would placed them far beyond a melee character who has to have some health and resists since they dont have that &quot;distance safey?&quot;<br />
<br />
2.) Limited Resource Management.<br />
<br />
A melee class should rarely, if ever, need to worry about &quot;running out&quot; of anything, but it should not be so for Casters/Ranged dps classes.<br />
<br />
While a Caster may have more damage POTIENTAL than a melee class, they should be limited by the amount of energy avalible to them.<br />
<br />
Here is where, imo, we have issues currently. Casters can reach HUUUUGE levels of energy, even while primarily focusing on heavy dps gear, to the point where they can say to hell with being efficient, im going to go full force 100% of the time.<br />
<br />
Casters need a reason to want to be efficient, thats the problem.<br />
<br />
Sorcerers using their efficient mode, and Necromancers using their more or less normal damage methods should be able to maintain their damage almost infinantly, while druids and psionicists should be able to maintain a moderate dps while trying to be efficient as well.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
A melee dps class should deal MORE damage than a caster thats fighting efficiently.<br />
<br />
BUT, when the need calls for it, the Caster should have the ability to &quot;rank up&quot; the damage at the cost of losing that infinant sustainability, thus known as &quot;the burn.&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
That right there is how you actually balance casters and melee damage in vanguard.<br />
<br />
Melee classes should be able to start out early in a fight doing strong, consistant damage over time, and while able to spike their damage a bit, they should have less &quot;max&quot; potiential than comparitive casters.<br />
<br />
Caster classes should be forced to have to fight efficiently or run the risk of droping to zero dps once their energy is gone from burning. Until their is a need for casters to fight efficiently, and if they are indeed designed in the up coming Revamps to have higher maximum potientials than Fighters, then there will indeed be little need for Fighter dps, except in &quot;specific&quot; fights where spell-based damage doesnt work well.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Basically, once a caster starts out lower, then ramps up higher in terms of dps when compared to a Fighter, they should balance out as equals once things are said an done.<br />
<br />
<br />
If a sorcerer in their &quot;efficient&quot; form starts out for the first 60 seconds of a fight doing 1500 dps while a rogue deals a constant average of 2000 dps, and then the sorcerer swaps to their burn form and starts to deal 2400 dps for 2 minutes and the fight is over, the total dps &quot;average&quot; for the sorcerer is 2033 dps, while the rogue has maintained a constant 2100 dps average, giving a slight ~ 5% advantage to a sorcerer.<br />
<br />
A sorcerer should be out of energy after a solid two minute straight burn, in which case they need to use GE or a shard to recover, both options that are limited and not always avalible, so in prolonged fights, fighters definatly would have an advantage.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
It all depends on what buffs they want to stack and how well they stack. Obviously the necroamcner's % based buff is part of a larger problem with casters having dispropotionally huge energy pools, but several other factors come into play as well.<br />
<br />
<br />
Until casters are limited more so by their energy pool, efficiency has no real noticable merit in their tactics, which means they are only limited by hate caps, which are likely to be &quot;fixed&quot; with in the next two game updates i would hope, which then leaves casters unchecked, free to deal more dps in almost all occasions than melee dps, basically a role reversal from what is currently in place.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
