	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1287693">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1287693">
                  
                  Rofl Code i've been saying that since Beta3!<br />
<br />
Skip to the very bottom if you want to find out how our spells are flawed at the base level, not just because of how the damage is calculated, but because of how they scale with Ranks vs a real spell scaling system (that is quite easy to set up). Read the section after the <font color="red">RED </font>text inorder to see my example of how &quot;scaling&quot; inbetween  the &quot;ranks&quot; of spells would allieviate several of our issues with some spells becoming &quot;hardly worth using&quot; inplace of others. Taqmirs and Char are weaker than several 50 spells simply because they have had a few levels in which their base damage is NOT improved with out level, hence especially why char is weak in the end game.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Here is the direct issue of caster-melee imbalances when it comes to damage scaling:<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Their abilities factor in their weapon/str as part of their base damage, and str adds a static amount onto their attack, which is then modified by their attacks when are % of attack + static, or attack + static, and only in the case of Monk's Kick skills and melee based  DOTS are the attacks actually static.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
MY disciple unbuffed has an attack of around 1000, with proper buff stacking, i can raise this to over 2500.<br />
<br />
My finishers calculate damage as 400% + static value, so you can see where that starts to compound quickly, especially with my high chance of critical hits, which also add more damage based on the base value.<br />
<br />
<br />
Intelligence is the only thing that effects base damage for casters, everything else then modifies the base damage.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Untill they change all caster-heald items to have a &quot;spell attack&quot; value and chance spells for casters to be &quot;300% of spell attack&quot; that is then modified by other stuff, casters will always lag behind in &quot;upgradability&quot; of their dps, and their spells will never retain the type of &quot;consistancy&quot; that melee attacks currently have (things such as always knowing X attack will be a certain amount stronger tha Y attack regardless of my level or Rank)<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Example, lets look at what they intend the base damage of one of our nukes to currently be, lets say they want a base damage of 4000 damage on Seradon.<br />
<br />
<br />
To work with that,  lets say they expect Seradon to be 800% spell attack rating to calculate the damage.<br />
<br />
Intellegence, in its new form, would add a straight amount of damage onto your spell attack.<br />
<br />
Using what ever value they expect the current &quot;100%&quot; base line to be at level 50 is what they would establish as the &quot;base line&quot; for how much intell is going to add to Spell Attack, lets say its +300 spell attack for now.<br />
<br />
A &quot;common&quot; spell attack rating on Common quality staff at level 50 might be around +200 spell attack, with a increased damage on spell critical hits due to being a two hander.<br />
<br />
So the weapon's damage + intell boost = a 500 spell attack rating.<br />
<br />
This spell now works its value off of this, meaning 800% of 500 = 4000 &quot;base&quot; damage if using the crappy gear of green quality with &quot;base&quot; intell.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Now, lets translate this to a caster who has a substantial amount of intell, and a very nice ultra rare crafted staff:<br />
<br />
The spell damage rating on this staff might be 280 now, and the boosted attack from intell might be 500 now, resulting in a spell attack of 780, multiple this by 800% for the spell, and your seradons falling star would hit for 6240.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Then once you start getting other buffs involved, these numbers start to grow even higher.<br />
<br />
<br />
For a melee class interested in daamge, you need only worry about 6 things:<br />
<br />
Weapon<br />
Str<br />
Dex<br />
+ Melee damage.<br />
+ mele crit<br />
+ melee accuracy<br />
<br />
(for survivability to sustain this damage in range of foes)<br />
Health, optional con.<br />
<br />
For a caster class interested in damage, you need only worry now about 6 things:<br />
<br />
Weapon<br />
Int<br />
Wisdom<br />
+ Spell damage rating.<br />
+ spell critic<br />
+ spell accuracy<br />
<br />
(for help in sustaining this daamge at range from foes)<br />
Energy, optional vitality.<br />
<br />
Casters shouldnt need to focus as much on health as they need to currently imo, it makes an unfair advantage for melee classes, as they have less stats that they NEED to focus on.<br />
<br />
<br />
Imo, if AOEs where changed to have less of a &quot;damage&quot; impact and more of a &quot;anti-caster&quot; impact, it would even the field.<br />
<br />
I dont think a caster should need to worry about dieing from most damage-based aoes, i think they should have to worry about silencing aoes, energy draining aoes, spell haste reducing aoes, and other things that are less fatal but equally detremental to a melee class having to withstand close range aoes that are tailored to hinder their game play (such as +end cost curses)<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I also think that ALL abilities should be based off of a % of the attack value, with no statics.<br />
<br />
That way spells like Seradons are always going to be = to &quot;so and so&quot; casts of Taqmir's.<br />
<br />
They could include seperate &quot;spell attack&quot; in different elements, similar to how spell focus currently works, that way if a staff has say a huge fire spell damage boost, but a poor arcane or cold boost, then we could tailor our offense for the particular fight we are in.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I think it would be much, much easier to balance spells and attack abilities if they are all based on the same attack value, as you can definatly make clear distinctions such as &quot;while Taqmir's is 250% spell damage, and costs 250 energy, Char might be 400% spell damage, with a slight reuse, and cost 500 energy&quot; or something of the sort, which makes it easier to figure out that char is going to hit harder, but be less efficient, while Taqmir will hit for less, but is much more efficient.<br />
<br />
On tool tips, they could include the math as well as the actual number:<br />
<br />
&quot;You stike your foe with a spear of flame, dealing 400% (5000) damage at max range, and 20% less damage with each meter away from max range&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
What would all this accomplish, besides making several devs but theri butts to convert over to this type of system?<br />
<br />
<br />
Spells would scale while still being in relation to each other as you level, and they would always keep pace with melee classes, and casters would have a REASON to really want that next staff, wand, or pair of foci, as it would make a rather strong impact on how hard they nuke.<br />
<br />
<br />
It would remove spell damage focus from gear, which means casters would have less stats to have to spread between on their gear, balancing them up with the melee classes who dont have to worry about &quot;melee damage focus&quot; currently since thats ALL based on their weapon(s).<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Energy costs on spells would be scaled from where they are currently, so that it would be a steady progression, w/o any &quot;ranks.&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
How do you do this? its really simple:<br />
<br />
Lets look at the actual costs on Taqmir's 4 vs 3:<br />
<br />
level 48<br />
298 Energy, returns 30-60 energy over 6 seconds<br />
<br />
vs<br />
<br />
level 42<br />
269 Energy, returns 25-50 energy over 6 seconds<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
The difference in energy is 29, and 5 - 10 on the over time feedback.<br />
<br />
So, if this spell is going to gradually approach the value by the time it eaches 48, you would divid the difference by the number of levels it takes to each this point, and you have your costs scaled so that you never have &quot;jumps&quot; like from level 47 to 48.<br />
<br />
<br />
The energy cost would be 4.833 per level, or for simplicity just round up to 5 more energy cost per level, but keep in mind that better gear and higher natural intellegence are going to be improving with each level, so chances are your efficiency is still improving.<br />
<br />
So, by level 46, you are 4 levels above 42, so 4.83 x 4 = 19.3, so +19 on the energy cost brings you to 288 energy cost, and by 48, it will be 298, the whole while the damage has scaled with your character's advancement though, vs being a static &quot;amount&quot; of damage from 42 to 47, then getting a big &quot;boost&quot; at 48 when the base damage catches up.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Basically, each rank of a spell, unless it actually adds something &quot;new&quot; over the old version, merely &quot;catches up&quot; your spell's base damage, which is why it appears to be an increase.<br />
<br />
<br />
Technically you can completely remove all cases of Rank abilities in this game by looking at the current differences in their &quot;ranks&quot; and dividing it amoung the levels between ranks, creating a smooth progression that has no scaling issues.<br />
<br />
Abilities that do get sudden jumps in effectiveness, like snare durations or %'s, could also gradually increase, rather than having a &quot;semi useless&quot; snare like rangers have at the lower levels that suddenly jumps high enough to be more useful for kiting, their snare could gradually get better and better as they appreach the level where they currently get the rank ii or iii versions.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Abilities that are based on a Static pool such as Phenomina points, Virtue points, or Endurance should never, ever need ranks, because if they are % based off a pool, they they will always be powerful compared to the other abilities that share that pool.<br />
<br />
If, for example, the absolute, only change in Starfall, a druid's phenomina, is that &quot;higher ranks do more damage,&quot; then there is no need for higher ranks, make it just an ability called &quot;starfall&quot; that improves as you level.<br />
<br />
If they want it to do 10k damage at 50, but only 3k at level 20, then scale it throughout so that its constantly improving with your character and never reaching a point where its &quot;pointless&quot; to cast it because your other nukes just got &quot;ranked up&quot; and rival it in power.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
You smoothe out the  &quot;jumps&quot; in effectivness when you scale abilities, and retain spell's power when compared to each other, as well as ensure that they will ALWAYS be strong, as they are all based off the same base attack stat for damage, rather than having different bases on different spells that are all being modified by a % based on intel/sdf/sdr and such.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>WARNING: The following is long winded and technical, the gist of the point is with Ranked abilities, lacking the constant increase of abilities that scale naturally with each level between these ranks, along with the issue of spells ranking up at different level intervals (6 for Taq, 8 for Char) you get extreme imbalances as you level up, where spells suddenly become &quot;good&quot; or &quot;bad&quot; in relation to other spells. Any time you &quot;rank up&quot; Char, its useful, but as soon as you get the next Taqmir's, Char loses a lot of its value has a dps tool.</b><br />
<br />
<br />
The following values are provider via Curse, which probably has no been updated to reflect the damage enhancement to the Taqmires spell line which only exasperates the issue im about to outline, but using what information I have, here are my findings:<br />
<br />
<br />
If Taqmir's is ment to be efficient, while Char is an inefficient damage &quot;boost&quot;, that should (and with scaling would) be retained form level 8 to level 50.<br />
<br />
Never will char &quot;lag behind&quot; taqmir, so that its &quot;worthless&quot; to use it compared to your newest rank of Taqmir until you get your &quot;new&quot; Char, Char will always be the higher dps option, with a bigger tax on your energy, while Taqmir would be the more efficient, but less burst damage option.<br />
<br />
Currently there are levels as you level up where using char is a detremental in most cases, as its energy cost and damage it produces is less effective than using a reciently aquired higher rank Taqmir.<br />
<br />
At level 6, Taqmirs does less damage than char, 168 damage but only costs 57 energy and returns 5-10, while char does a total of 238 damage but costs 83 energy. They are balance, with different uses.<br />
<br />
Right at the start, the player learns that if energy conservation is an issue, use Taqmir and ignore char, and if speedy dps is desired, use char then a taqmir.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
But go forward just a few levels and you fight that at level 12, Taqmir's <u>new </u>rank is now 288 damage, and costs 94 energy and returns 5 - 15 energy, but now it has a 2.5 casting time, yet still out out dpses char by a long shot merely cast back to back, and is more efficient still.<br />
<br />
You are still stuck with Char 1 for now, which deals less damage for almost the exact same cost, and will not deliver this damage as quickly as the new Taqmirs.<br />
<br />
By 14, you get the next char, which is 447 damage for 137 energy, which is now more effective than taqmirs once more for fast damage, but is much less efficient.<br />
<br />
But then again at 18, you get yet again the new taqmir, which is now hitting for 417 for 127 energy, returning 10-20 energy, which again dwards the damage added by Char with a lower energy cost, energy feedback, and other factors that make using char just not worth it until it gets ranked up again at level 22.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
See the cycle of Char becoming worthless because it is not scaling as quickly as Taqmir's with ranks, then suddenly becoming &quot;uber&quot; for a few levels, until the next Taqmir is aquired? The only time this is not the case is level 6 and 30, when they both simultainously rank up.<br />
<br />
<br />
If these were constant, at 18 when we would get the &quot;new taq&quot; for 417 damage at 127 energy (before feedback of 10-20), the damage on a scaling Char should be 560 at 165 energy, as it has been 4 levels past level 14. One cast of char scaled is worth 125% damage of Taq, but costs +23% more.<br />
<br />
If i had the time i would show a spreadsheet of how the base damages of spells could scale, and you would quickly see that they correlate to each other well enough for a % based system to be established.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<b><font color="Red"><font size="5">IMPORTANT</font></font></b><br />
<br />
I can give no better example than to show the level 30 versions, where the line up compared to eachother, to what they should be at level 46, when you recieve the final version of char.<br />
<br />
If you compare the level 30 versions, the only level where they actually match up besides level 6, you find that a single cast of char costs +22% more than a single cast of Taq's Barrage at 30, at +124% damage per cast, now look how that compares to my earlier example of how the &quot;scaled&quot; cost on Char would have made it +125% damage of taq in a single cast, with a cost that is +23% more.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now that you have seen the values of how a &quot;scaled&quot; char matches up with the actual level 18 Taqmir 4, compare the highest ranks for how much a 2 level difference in scaling acounts for:<br />
<br />
At 46/48, a single cast costs 17% more energy than Taqmir before the feedback is calculated, and only deals 19% more damage per cast.<br />
<br />
If we look at a scaled version of Taqmir to see what it &quot;should&quot; be at 46 for and equal comparison, it ends up as 287 energy, which when compared to the actual level 46 char, it ends up as ~21% more energy per cast with Char at 23% more damage per cast, much closer to my intended scaled values.<br />
<br />
Also, these spells would be scaled up to level 50, so they would be closer to the damage of your current level 50 spells and would correlate better with them.<br />
<br />
Char V deals 1183 damage at 304 cost, Char VI deals 1462 damage at 361 cost.<br />
<br />
So in 8 levels the damage as increased by 19%, and the cost has increased by 16%, so using those values to estimate what Char VII would be at level 54, we could assume it is 1740 damage at 420 energy.<br />
<br />
<b>Char at level 50, if we follow the paturns of what the previous ranks established, it should cost 391 Energy and deal 1601 damage if Char scaled properly each level from 46 to 50.</b><br />
<br />
Using the same method to see what Taqmir should be at 50 when scaled:<br />
<br />
Taqmir's at 42 deals 1036 damage at 269 cost, and at 48 it deals 1178 damage at 298 cost, so it increases its damage by 12% and cost by 10% in 6 levels, so at 54 it would estimated to be 1319 damage at 328 cost.<br />
<br />
Using those values, since taqmir's gains 141 damage and 30 energy cost over that 6 level span, it gains 23.5 damage and 5 energy cost per level.<br />
<br />
<b>The level 50 scaled Taqmir's Barrage would be damage 1225 damage at a 308 cost.</b><br />
<br />
<br />
So, when comparing spell damage, if we actually scaled our spells properly, they would be much closer to the level 50 spells in terms of potientially being used.<br />
<br />
Certainly some spells simply are too weak at the base level when compared to our other spells, but scaling is certainly a large part of the problem.<br />
<br />
Since these are the base values, the shear differince in damage is only expanded when you add intelligence, +%damage abilities, spell damage focus, spell damage rating, and other modifiers.<br />
<br />
The slight damage boost at the base level doesnt seem like it would make a huge impact, but once you star getting into the modifiers, it makes a DYNAMIC impact on final damage numbers.
                  
		</div>
